BRUSSELS, July 15 (Reuters) - EU antitrust chief Margrethe Vestager on Friday said she has a few merger deals in sight where she may use powers endorsed this week by Europe's second-top court which allow her to scrutinise so-called 'killer' acquisitions. The Luxembourg-based General Court on Wednesday backed the European Commission's Article 22 power to examine deals where companies do not have any activities or revenue in the 27-country European Union in a case involving Illumina (ILMN.O) and Grail (GRAL.O).  read more  "We have a few acquisitions within our sights that may be relevant candidates for Article 22. But that is not a given," Vestager told a news conference, without providing details. Killer acquisitions typically refer to big companies acquiring rival start-ups to close them down. Our Standards: The Thomson Reuters Trust Principles.